## Addressing — MAC and IP

### MAC Address
- Permanent physical hardware address (Wi-Fi card, Bluetooth card)
- Cannot be physically altered
- Used for device tracking

### IP Address
- Unique identifier for devices on a network
- **IPv4** — 32-bit, four octets (e.g. 127.0.0.1), ~4 billion combinations
- **IPv6** — 128-bit alphanumeric, infinite combinations, better security

### IP Classes
| Class | Range | Used by |
|---|---|---|
| A | 0–127 | Large ISPs |
| B | 128–191 | Cities, medium networks |
| C | 192–223 | Small/home networks |
| D | — | Multicast |
| E | — | Scientists and testing |

### Static vs Dynamic IP
- **Static** — never changes, used for DNS and servers
- **Dynamic** — assigned randomly by DHCP from a pool

### ARP — Address Resolution Protocol
Translates IP addresses into MAC addresses using request and reply.
**ARP Spoofing** — attacker sends fake ARP requests to intercept data

### VLAN — Virtual LAN
Logically divides a single physical network into multiple separated networks using 802.1Q tagging.
Example: isolating HR, Dev, and Sales departments on the same physical network.

